# Factorio solver

This is my attempt to find the most-ideal factory layout in
[Factorio](https://www.factorio.com). Since this is not a tutorial, I
won't be covering game mechanics, rules, etc. I assume the primary
objective of what follows is to launch satellites into orbit.


## Overview

There are two problems we must solve: 1) determining the set of machines
required to produce rockets and 2) the optiminum geographical layout of
these machines. While the first problem is hard, it's already been
solved thanks to the [Factorio Calculator by Kirk McDonald]. The second
problem is much harder.


## Machines required to produce rockets

The factory required to produce rockets can be thought of as a [directed
acyclic graph], where each node represents a machine that converts inputs
to outputs (e.g. assembling machine), and edges are the inputs and
outputs (e.g. gear wheel):

![factorio graph]

Using Kirk McDonald's Factorio calculator, we can compute the machines
required to construct the factory for this process:

1. build a rocket silo
2. build a satellite factory
3. build a [rocket part] factory
4. wait for 100 rocket parts and 1 satellite to be built
5. insert the satellite into the silo and launch

Knowing the set of machines required for this process is only half of
the problem – we also have to layout the factory on the surface.


## Optimum layout

In order to compute the optimium geographical layout for our rocket
factory, we must first define what "optimum" means. While there are many
objectives we might try to minimize, the ones relating to geographic
layout include:

1. geographic area required
2. number of belts
3. disorder – proximity of similar machines, "straightness" of belts, etc.
4. buffer sizes – items on belts and in machines; this is related to #2

The objectives above likely contain trade-offs. For instance, minimizing
area may increase disorder by requiring more underground belts.

Similarly, minimizing number of belts might require more geographic
area. For example, a long sequence of belts might allow one group of
related machines to be squeezed into the space leftover other sections
of the factory.
